post_text:
Attention parents of students in Early Childhood, PK, Kindergarten, 6th and 9th Grades and Seniors! This information was emailed today regarding health requirements.
Per Illinois School Code, students in these grades will still need to submit the required health documents for their grade, even though we will be learning remotely. The requirement is for any student enrolled in school and is not contingent on in-person instruction.
Because of the current circumstances we are extending the deadline for physicals and immunizations this year to October 15, 2020. Please contact the nurse if you have questions or need help meeting this requirement.
Please use the link below to access the health requirements letter.
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EfWz4xqI4a7wk9T3kSP5ezPBo81uLnIdFsGrGizp31s/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
Dear New Berlin CUSD #16 Families, Students, and Parents:

I hope this message finds you and your families safe and well. Today, Illinois Gov. JB Pritzker announced that remote learning in Illinois will be extended through April 30th in order to slow down the spread of COVID-19.

During this time, on-site learning will remain suspended but our schools’ commitment to learning and education will remain open and learning will continue for all students - just through a different format.

While it is not ideal, we want to assure you that at New Berlin CUSD #16, our administrators, teachers, and support staff are fully engaged and willing to take on this new challenge as we push forward with remote learning, engaging with students and continuing with our food distribution program.

I know this is not the school year that any of us imagined, but I want to thank you for your patience and understanding as we deal with this unprecedented situation together.
Sincerely,
Dr. Adam Ehrman
Superintendent, New Berlin CUSD #16
Pretzel Pride!

Kara Merkley Pecoraro is feeling blessed with New Berlin HS.
March 25 at 6:42 PM ·

Dom told me jokingly that he is worried about his teachers. They have been posting things at midnight, 5 am... Just think about that. In the middle of all this craziness, teachers continue to stay up late and wake up at the crack of dawn to help their students learn. Providing content, not to assess, not to prepare for a standardized test, but to educate and provide a little bit of "normal" in the middle of a global pandemic. Thank you, from the bottom of my heart, thank you.

post_text:
Dear New Berlin CUSD #16 Families,
On Friday, March 20, Illinois State Governor J.B. Pritzker, announced during a press conference that all Illinois residents will be in a “stay at home” order starting Saturday, March 21 at 5:00 pm until the end of April 7. Governor Pritzker also stated that Illinois public and private schools will be extending the closure through Tuesday, April 7 due to the COVID-19 virus.

At this time with our scheduled spring break, the timing of Good Friday, and Easter weekend, our schools are tentatively scheduled to resume on Tuesday, April 14 until further notice and/or future executive orders. Please stay safe.

Sincerely,

Dr. Adam Ehrman
Superintendent, New Berlin CUSD #16
Pretzel Pride!

post_text: As we continue to carefully assess the ever-changing COVID-19 situation, New Berlin School District has decided to adjust our Grab and Go meals schedule. In the interest of the health of our staff and community members, we want to minimize uneccessary exposure risks by offering the Grab and Go meals on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays each week rather than each day. Beginning Monday, March 23rd, we will be providing meals on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays from 9am - 11am. Monday’s pick up will contain Monday and Tuesday meals, Wednesday will contain Wednesday and Thursday meals, and Friday will contain Friday’s meals. As before, please come to the circle drive at the elementary school. PLEASE STAY IN YOUR VEHICLE. We will bring the meals out to you.

Horace Mann
December 19, 2019 at 8:55 PM ·

In the spirit of giving, our employees donated $3,000 to HMGives to DonorsChoose, an employee-driven fundraiser thanking educators in three of our office locations, including 20 classrooms in Sangamon County, Illinois, one in Irving, Texas and another in Durham, North Carolina.

Altogether, the projects completed include iPads, movie tickets, seat sacks, wiggle chairs, math and science tools, headphones and more. Educators estimate more than 700 students will benefit from the donated supplies. Way to go, Horace Mann employees! #LifeAtHoraceMann

These are just safety drills and we are just practicing our safety procedures.
